<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Survey of Personal Pension Plans (10): A Sipp will cost less
and allow you to have more control - Pensions for high earners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employees, the self-employed and business partners who can afford to pay
Pounds 5,000 a year or more into their personal plan, and who want greater
control over the investment process, should consider a self-invested
personal pension (Sipp).
The key feature of this product is that it separates the two main functions
usually combined under a typical life office plan - namely, the investment
management and administration. This adds considerable flexibility to the
arrangement.
First, you can manage the investments yourself, although most people prefer
to appoint a stockbroker.
Second, you can see exactly what you are paying for the administration and
investment management, whereas the cost of these functions can be blurred
under a standard plan.
Third, if you are unhappy with the performance, you can change the
investment manager yet leave the underlying administration in place. This
avoids the early termination penalties that often apply when you stop
payments to regular-premium personal pensions.
Eddy Woore, manager for personal plans with pension provider Pointon York,
said: 'For investors prepared to contribute Pounds 5,000 or more to their
plan, the flat-rate charges associated with Sipps are definitely cheaper
than the percentage charges imposed by conventional plans. Moreover there
are no policy conditions, so you can transfer out or retire early without
penalty.'
Only a few providers offer the administration and legal package you need to
run a Sipp. Pointon York and Personal Pension Management (PPM) specialise in
this market, while several firms of stockbrokers, solicitors and chartered
accountants have launched their own Sipps. Most use PPM's legal and
administration services.
Investment management charges will vary, but for the basic shell Pointon
York charges a Pounds 600 set-up fee and a Pounds 400 annual management
charge. PPM has several charging structures, depending on the level of
service required. For the full service you would pay a combined set-up and
annual management charge of Pounds 800 in the first year and an annual
management charge of Pounds 400 thereafter. If you are only interested in
investment trusts, then the fee would be Pounds 456 for the first year and
Pounds 228 thereafter. As a rule of thumb, the investment trust Sipp is
cost-effective for annual contributions of Pounds 2,500 to Pounds 3,000 or
more.
The rules on Sipp contribution limits and benefits are the same as those for
personal pensions, but there the similarity ends. Most conventional plans
allow you to invest only in the provider's funds, although one or two offer
links to other investment managers.
Mr Woore commented: 'Some personal pension plans give you access to external
funds, but usually there is an extra annual management charge which makes
this route very expensive. With a Sipp, there is no second tier of annual
charges.'
Under a Sipp, you can invest in:
Stocks and shares (eg, equities, gilts, debentures) quoted on the UK Stock
Exchange, and including securities on the Unlisted Securities Market;
Stocks and shares traded on a recognised overseas stock exchange;
Unit trusts and investment trusts;
Offshore funds (recognised by the Securities and Investments Board);
Insurance company managed funds and unit-linked funds;
Deposit accounts; and
Commercial property.
Professional firms find commercial property an attractive option. A Sipp
fund cannot purchase a firm's existing business premises from the
partnership, but it can buy new offices into which the partnership can move,
provided the property is leased back on a commercial basis.
Furthermore, a Sipp can borrow on the strength of the pension fund, to help
with property purchase, although it cannot lend part of the pension fund to
scheme members.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
