<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Survey of Personal Pension Plans (7): Pick a long-term
achiever - Performance: why it is so hard to pin down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Performance arguably is the most important factor that affects the final
value of your fund at retirement, but it cannot be seen in isolation.
Charges and contract flexibility must also be considered, as these may
reduce overall returns considerably.
However, whereas providers' charges and contract flexibility can now be
assessed with some degree of accuracy, good performance remains a
notoriously elusive creature.
Five years is a long time in investment management, as the table with this
article illustrates, yet there are still many providers keen to lock
investors in for 20 years or more.
Using past performance as a guide to the future clearly is risky, but with
careful analysis the process can provide a more reliable indication of what
is to come.
Consultants and actuaries Bacon &amp; Woodrow supplied the five star guide to
performance used in Table 1, on page 2 of this survey. The performance
screens eliminated funds that achieved below-average returns, were
inconsistent or volatile.
Andrew Warwick-Thompson, head of partnership pensions at B&amp;W, explained the
process: 'The use of past performance statistics is probably the best guide
to gauge future performance, provided it is coupled with a clear
understanding of how past performance was achieved, an assessment of the
current investment style of a management team and a knowledge of whether the
individuals responsible for past performance are still in place.'
The screening process examined performance over quarterly time periods in
the three-, four- and five-year periods ending 31 March, 1994.
The following tests relate to the five-star ratings.
Screen 1 excluded funds whose average percentile score was below 50.5.
Screen 2 selected those funds which had appeared in the top two quartiles
most frequently and in the bottom quartile least frequently. This weeded out
funds that passed the first screening yet were consistently below median.
Funds were awarded two stars if they had appeared in the top two quartiles
more than 11 times and in the bottom quartile less than five times over the
20 quarterly time periods.
Screen 3 selected funds that achieved low volatility. This third star was
awarded where the percentile scores had below average standard deviation.
Screen 4 examined performance trends. Graphs were plotted showing the
percentile scores, and a 'best fit' line was drawn through these moving
average points. Those funds with an upward trend were awarded a fourth star.
Screen 5 involved a series of interviews with fund managers who had passed
the first four tests. The interviews were based on responses to a
questionnaire which sought details on, among other points, the growth in
size of the managed fund, contributions and withdrawals, the number of
managers and analysts on the fund management team, the asset allocation and
stock selection processes, the background of the principals of the team and
the fees charged to the fund which are not included in the published annual
management charges.
Several managers were awarded a fifth star on the basis of the interview
results.
Only funds with a five-year record and Pounds 20m under management made it
through to the final shortlist. This excluded Professional Life's external
funds (managed by Morgan Grenfell and Gartmore) and Mercury Life's fund,
although B&amp;W stressed that in other respects these were 'promising'.
We asked Bacon &amp; Woodrow to provide a star rating for all managed
unit-linked funds, although several of the poor performers in particular
declined the invitation to take part in today's survey.
Looking purely at performance, five stars were awarded to: Gartmore, Legal &amp;
General, M&amp;G, Norwich Union, Standard Life and Sun Life.
Four stars were awarded to Abbey Life, Allied Dunbar, Britannia Life,
Clerical Medical, Commercial Union, Equitable, General Accident, Hambro
Guardian, Irish Life (Opportunity fund), Lincoln National, London &amp;
Manchester, Prudential (corporate fund), Royal London and TSB.
At the other end of the spectrum, all too many failed even to gain one star.
These include AEgon, Albany, Axa Equity &amp; Law (balanced fund), Barclays
Life, Canada Life, Century Group, Colonial Mutual, Confederation Life,
Cornhill, Crown, General Portfolio, Hearts of Oak, Laurentian, London Life,
Manulife, MGM, Midland, National Provident, Premium Life, Provident Life
(apart from the S&amp;F balanced fund), Provident Mutual, Prudential (but the
corporate fund achieved four stars), Royal Life, Save &amp; Prosper, Scottish
Amicable, Scottish Mutual, Scottish Widows, Skandia (own fund), Sun Alliance
(own fund) and Windsor Life.
Moreover, bear in mind that data was not available for a significant
proportion of providers. If the entry shows 'no data', this may be because
it is a relatively new fund - but it is important that you check this point.
Bacon &amp; Woodrow operates on a fee basis, and in practice also excludes
providers which are not prepared to strip out the commission costs and
reinvest this in the fund.
Further screening with B&amp;W's survey analysed contract terms similar to the
product flexibility ratings in Table 1. On this basis, several providers
awarded four and five stars purely on performance would not be recommended
by the firm.
Bacon &amp; Woodrow's advice stresses that long-term consistency should be
favoured above the occasional years of exceptional returns achieved by the
more volatile managers. Indeed, there is considerable danger attached to
chasing last year's 'winners'.
John Sheffield, senior partner with pensions advisers and employee benefits
consultants AIS Pensions, said: 'The publicity given to the 'top five' funds
can make them an irresistible draw to the pension purchaser and produce a
business bonanza for the companies concerned.'
Sheffield analysed survey statistics over a five-year period to show how the
top managers in 1989 fared over the following five years. The results (see
the table with this article) are startling:
'Out of 1989's top five, only London &amp; Manchester maintained a high position
in the subsequent five years, but even here there is need for caution. L&amp;M
have two personal pension contracts, and under the wrong one you would have
found yourself in 71st place,' he said.
Bacon &amp; Woodrow Personal Pension Handbook and Unit Linked Survey 1994/95 is
available from NTC Publications Ltd, Farm Road, Henley-on-Thames,
Oxfordshire RG9 1EJ. Tel:01491 574671. Price Pounds 27.50.
 ---------------------------------------
WHERE ARE THEY NOW?
 ---------------------------------------
Pension                1989         1994
provider           position     position
 ---------------------------------------
Colonial Mutual         1st        73rd*
Provident Mutual        2nd         60th
London &amp; Manchester     3rd          8th
British Life            4th         77th
Confederation Life      5th         70th
Funds surveyed           58           82
 ---------------------------------------
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Figures apply to results for a Pounds 200 per month, five-year
regular-premium plan. *Colonial Mutual did not provide figures for the
1994 survey, so this figure was calculated by AIS based on their 1989
charging structure and the five-year returns on their managed fund.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Personal Pensions 1989 and 1994
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
