<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Survey of Personal Pension Plans (8): How to read the vital
statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As concern mounts over the future survival of so many life offices,
investors should vet providers' credentials thoroughly before parting with
their cash.
Consulting actuaries AKG, which provides technical information within the
financial services market, produced a 'vital statistics' checklist for
investors, drawn from its financial-strength reports on UK insurance
companies*. Here, we use Standard Life's vital statistics to illustrate the
checkpoints.
Standard Life: The vital statistics. . .
Type of organisation: Mutual.
Life offices can be mutuals or proprietary. Mutuals effectively are owned by
their policyholders - they cannot raise finance on the stockmarket.
Proprietary companies ought to give the life office capital security, but
they also have to pay dividends to shareholders.
Ultimate owner: Standard Life.
As a mutual, Standard's ownership requires no further investigation. The
point about available capital may be important, as competition intensifies
and profit margins reduce. Owners of proprietary life offices should be
vetted for the same reasons.
Funds under management: Pounds 30,738bn.
As the largest mutual in the UK, Standard Life's financial strength is
unquestioned. For other life offices, this figure provides a useful
indicator of size and commercial muscle. As a further indicator, you should
also look at last year's new business figures:
Free asset ratio: 17.04 per cent.
This refers to assets in excess of those held to meet liabilities, expressed
as a percentage of total assets. Free asset ratios generally are higher for
providers of with profits funds, which use the free assets to support
current and future business.
*For details on the 'Vital statistics' guide and the financial strength
reports on UK insurance companies, contact: AKG, The Old Dutch House, 134
High Street, Dorking RH4 1BG. Tel: 01306 876439. Fax: 885325.
</TEXT>
