<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Survey of Personal Pension Plans (4): Shop carefully in the
new year - The charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
From next week, many personal pension providers will slash sales commissions
and other charges deducted in the early years of long-term personal pension
plans.
The result will be a better deal for investors prepared to shop around -
provided that is, they know what to look for. Worth considering are the
providers with good performance with modest charges and flexible contracts
that allow you to stop or reduce premiums and retire early without penalty
(see Table 1).
Standard Life announced in October that, from January 1, it would no longer
penalise investors who stop premiums or transfer their fund to another
provider. Life offices that sell through independent advisers must follow
suit if they are to survive in the post-disclosure competitive environment.
Standard's changes are timely. As of today, it breaks its link with the
Halifax which no longer exclusively sells Standard's products through its
vast branch network.
The move away from 'front-end loading' (where charges are heaviest in the
early years) has been accompanied by the introduction of flexible sales
commissions for independent advisers (see facing page). This makes it even
more difficult for investors looking for the best value, since the amount of
commission taken by the adviser is deducted from premiums and naturally
affects the value of your fund.
Our tables assume standard rates of commission are paid, but in practice
from January 1995 many providers will allow the adviser to take anything
from nil (for the fee-based advisers) up to the current maximum, which can
virtually wipe out the first year's premiums on a long-term contract.
The commission and charges will depend on the type of contract. Tables 1 and
2 examine charges for regular and recurring single-premium plans. Regular
plans traditionally have carried the high front-end charges that result in
such poor value for early transfers. Recurring single-premium (RSP) plans
should deduct only those charges associated with each premium and therefore
provide better value for those who stop premiums in the early years.
Jon Minchin, managing director of independent adviser Pensionline, said:
'From January 1995, an adviser who sells you a standard regular-premium plan
with all the associated charges will not be offering best advice.' However,
Minchin warned that some of the alternative RSP contracts are nothing of the
sort, and still carry regular premium charges.
Bear in mind that RSP contracts are designed for employees who intend to
save on a regular basis. Francis Moore, operations director with pension
provider PPM, said: 'The self-employed and partners do not want this type of
contract, but instead should look for total flexibility over the timing and
level of contributions to suit their business cash flow.' These investors
would do best with a single-premium plan that allows them to pay what they
want when they want.
One further point - if your plan was well chosen, you may be able to
transfer your fund without penalty, but to little avail if your adviser
takes full commission on investing your transfer value with a new provider.
The golden rule here is to check the provider's and adviser's costs every
time you take action, whether transferring or simply increasing premiums
(another notorious trigger point for fresh charges).
More than 100 providers were invited to take part in this survey. Some were
still in the process of revising their charges right up to the end of
December and could not take part. Others simply refused. If your provider is
not in Table 1 and 2, ask for the reason and request the information so that
you can make up your own mind whether the plan represents good value and the
performance is satisfactory.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
    P6311 Life Insurance.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COSTS  Service costs &amp; Service prices.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
