<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Survey of Personal Pension Plans (1): The new deal for
investors - The UK's first life and pensions products were sold in 1762.
Now, 233 years later, the life offices must at last disclose the full extent
of their charges. This survey is by Debbie Harrison
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Next week a quiet revolution takes place, which will transform the way
financial products are sold in the UK and improve dramatically investors'
rights.
From January 1, 1995 the Securities and Investment Board, the chief
regulator, and the Personal Investments Authority, the regulator for
providers and advisers of financial services, require life offices and those
who sell their products to tell prospective clients how much they deduct in
charges.
Later in the year, providers of all other investments covered by the
Financial Services Act - such as unit trusts, investment trusts and personal
equity plans - will be required to comply with the new rules.
Previously, investors could look at the life office's 'illustration' of what
their fund might be worth at maturity and be utterly misled. To calculate
the illustration or 'projection', the life office had to make two important
assumptions - the level of charges and the growth rate. Before 1988, there
was no regulation as to what charges should be disclosed. Providers could
also pick and choose the growth rate. Often the best-ever annual return
achieved by the company was chosen to represent expected growth over a
25-year period - hence the notorious telephone-number projections associated
with the industry at that time.
In 1988, the regulators, under the Financial Services Act, curbed the more
ridiculous projections by enforcing the use of standard growth rates.
Unfortunately they also insisted that providers use in these projections a
standard basis for charges that bore no relation to actual deductions. As a
result, the life offices with low charges could not demonstrate the good
value they offered, while the high chargers could hide their exorbitant
costs behind the 'standard' format.
Under this system, most investors had no idea how much of their money was
disappearing in charges, and when. Salesmen urged clients to sign up for
long-term regular-premium contracts (monthly and annual), because the
commission they themselves would receive was higher. Sales commission was,
and in most cases still is, based on the level of premium and the number of
years to maturity. Most of the commission relating to the entire term was
paid in advance immediately after the sale.
Providers argued that this system was fair. Yet they obscured the heavy
upfront charges by an actuarial sleight of hand. Investors' premiums in the
early years would buy 'capital' or 'initial' units, which carry a punitive
charge for the entire contract term. Alternatively, the 'allocation rate'
(the amount of your premium actually invested) would be low in the early
years.
Either way, if a policyholder stopped paying premiums during the first few
years of a long-term contract, he or she could be left empty-handed. Figures
on pages 2 and 3 of this survey show this can still happen. If you sign up
for a 20-year regular-premium personal pension, paying Pounds 2,400 a year,
but stop after one year, you will get nothing back from British Life Office,
Crown Financial, Hambro Guardian, Irish Life and Lifetime. If you stop after
five years, most life offices offer a transfer value worth less than the
amount you have paid in.
Providers defended this practice by pointing to the often excellent returns
available after 25 years. Yet they are reluctant to reveal how many of their
clients actually make it this far. Office of Fair Trading research indicates
that only one in seven long-term endowment policies ever reaches maturity.
For the rest, the investment can represent a costly mistake.
The threat of full disclosure of charges has concentrated life office minds
wonderfully. In the run-up to the January 1995 regime, they pondered whether
investors would still commit themselves for a 20- or 25-year term if they
first saw the penalties for pulling out early. Their conclusion was a
resounding 'no', judging by the flurry of revamped charging structures
launched in recent weeks.
Life offices realise that they must spread their costs over the entire term
to make early-surrender deals look better. Allied Dunbar, Standard Life and
the Prudential are among those which have already taken this step. Equitable
Life has always operated this system.
But life assurance is a slow-moving industry, and many offices were
reluctant to see the writing on the wall. Some providers whose figures are
not present in this report were still revising their charging structure only
days ago.
The new rules do not prevent life offices from selling poor-quality and
expensive products - what they do is to make it easier for the investor to
avoid them. For the regime to work, investors should seek independent advice
from a specialist who has the software to compare quotations across the
entire range of providers.
Unfortunately, many will not, because a significant proportion of consumers
do not understand the difference between company representatives (direct
salesmen and tied agents), who by law can only recommend the products of the
life office they represent, and independent advisers, whose job it is to
select the most suitable product on the market.
Some of the largest providers are direct-sales operations. Equitable Life,
the Prudential, Pearl, and Allied Dunbar sell most of their products this
way. So do the 'bancassurers' - the banks and building societies that use
their high-street outlets to sell products generated by their life assurance
companies.
Barclays, Lloyds, National Westminster, Abbey National, Midland, Royal Bank
of Scotland, TSB, Britannia, the Woolwich, National &amp; Provincial and, from
January 1995, the Halifax, all operate in this way. (Some also operate an
independent advice service, but only for clients who ask.)
Most of the remaining banks and building societies, with a few exceptions,
do not give independent advice, but sell the products of just the one life
office to which they are tied. The most notable exception is the Bradford &amp;
Bingley, which does offer independent financial advice.
Independent advice is widely available, but still forms a minority sales
outlet - over two thirds of regular-premium life and pensions business is
sold by direct-sales operations.
Of course, independent advice is not necessarily expert advice. Advisers
have a mixed reputation, and the new regime will not turn the cowboy element
into competent professionals. Moreover, the new rules only apply to charges.
Some of the lowest chargers offer poor performance, while some of the top
performers are also the most expensive. A competent adviser will marry
reasonable charges with good performance, and also consider the flexibility
of the contract terms, among other factors.
The new rules on charges will be phased in over the next few months,
although most large life offices operate the full system from January 1.
Stage 1: January 1, 1995. From this date, direct salesmen, tied agents and
independent advisers must tell prospective clients the exact amount they
will receive in commission from the product provider after the sale is
completed.
They must also show details of the provider's actual charges over the term
of the contract. This will show what your fund may be worth if you stop
payments during the early years.
However, these details initially do not have to be 'client specific' (in the
regulators' jargon). This means that the example used to illustrate the
provider's charges will be based on a hypothetical case, and does not have
to relate to your own investment details.
Stage 2: July 1, 1995. The provider's own charges for each particular sale
must be explained clearly. All of this information is set out in detail in a
'key features' document, which the adviser or salesman personally must hand
over to the prospective client before the sale is made.
Debbie Harrison is the author of Pension Power, a consumer guide to
pensions, to be published by John Wiley and Sons in late January (price,
Pounds 9.99).
</TEXT>
