<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Survey of Personal Pension Plans (2): Make sure your plan is
a portable one - As competition increases, more than 40 life offices may go
out of business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Recent research by the consultants and actuaries Bacon &amp; Woodrow suggested
that at least 40 of more than 100 life offices currently trading were likely
to disappear by the end of the century.
This would be a direct result of the new disclosure requirements and the
consequent competition to reduce charges.
The same report said that only 10 per cent of existing offices are cost
effective, and added: 'The remainder, mostly traditional life offices, are
leaving themselves open to attack by the new, lower-cost, simple-savings
providers.'
For 'traditional' read old-style mutual. Mutuals are life offices that do
not have shareholders but instead distribute profits to members, unlike the
proprietary offices that are quoted on the stock exchange and can call on
shareholders for extra cash.
Some of the mutuals have proved less than adept at modernising their product
range. Others are so small that they cannot afford the investment in
marketing and information technology necessary to survive.
The long arm of the Department of Trade and Industry will ensure that the
rationalisation process takes the form of a series of takeovers and mergers,
not insolvencies. The DTI closely monitors the solvency of insurance
companies through the annual returns.
A DTI spokesman said: 'It is unlikely we would let the solvency position of
an insurance company get to the stage where it was in dire straits. If a
company appeared to be getting into difficulties, we would try to encourage
a takeover or merger. We would certainly try to avoid an insolvency. This
would harm the insurance industry's image and would not be in the best
interests of policyholders.'
In the unlikely event of a life office insolvency, investors would be
protected by the Policyholders Protection Act 1975 and receive 90 per cent
of the value of their plans at the time the company crashed.
In addition to the small life offices, Bacon &amp; Woodrow identified two
further 'at risk' categories. These were the subsidiaries of foreign
companies and the broad-based, medium-sized life offices that try to be all
things to all men - and in practice do nothing very well.
Two recognisable groups emerge as survivors - the bancassurers, which
produce their own products to sell through their extensive high-street
branch networks, and life offices that concentrate on specialist products
sold through independent advisers.
In theory a rationalisation of life offices should be welcomed. Currently,
over 100 insurance companies produce life and pensions products, the
majority of which depend totally, or to a great extent, on their
direct-sales force to sell their products. If the high chargers and poor
performers go to the wall, then the blood-letting will leave behind a
healthier financial services industry. Unfortunately, in many cases the
criteria for survival will not be based on excellence but on commercial
muscle.
The streamlined insurance sector is likely therefore to be dominated by the
giants, most of which sell the bulk, if not all, of their products through
company representatives.
If you plan to take out a long-term pension or life assurance-linked
investment, your adviser should look for a provider that is likely to be
around in 10 to 20 years' time when your policy matures.
Consulting actuaries AKG carried out research into life assurance and
pension providers' backgrounds. Managing director Nick Anderton said:
'Investors and their advisers should examine, among other factors, a
company's ownership, its size, its backing, its relative position in the
market, and the way it distributes its products. The last point may be
important in terms of distribution costs, and hence the charges. Careful
analysis of the provider's background should avoid turning the selection
process into a lottery.'
However, if inadvertently you do invest with a life office that subsequently
is taken over, what assurances do you have that your fund will continue to
be well managed? One theory is that a fund closed to new business following
takeover should do well, because it does not bear any new business costs.
For this reason, some advisers are thought to be recommending funds on the
assumption that the provider will be taken over.
Their logic has merit and may well prove to be accurate where the takeover
was a result of synergy rather than impecuniosity. But bear in mind that, if
you were originally sold a poor investment, an acquiring company is under no
obligation to reduce excessive charges or remove high early-termination
penalties.
The best way to avoid storing up future problems for yourself is to make
sure your personal pension is genuinely flexible and portable. If it is, you
should be able to transfer out at any time without penalty, and your adviser
should not take a fresh chunk of commission on the transfer in to the new
provider.
</TEXT>
