<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Weekend Money: Permanent interest-bearing shares
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Pibs are the closest you can get to holding ordinary shares in a
building society. They are fixed interest securities with no redemption
date - so your capital cannot be guaranteed. You can realise your
investment only by selling them on the open market - with the chance of
capital gain or loss. They provide a relatively high yield, as the
table shows. This is partly because a building society is theoretically
not obliged to pay out if doing so would drive it into loss. Also, the
market is relatively small and the shares are not always easy to buy
and sell.
