<PROFILE>_AN-FAAACADHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941231
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Revenue is right -
Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I am the trustee of a discretionary trust for my grandson (a minor). Its
capital is invested in a government deposit bond, and the sole income is the
gross interest which this bond pays annually. The Inland Revenue bases its
tax demand of 35 per cent each year on the previous year's actual interest.
Because of the declining interest rates of recent years, this has meant that
the tax levied on each year's actual income is, effectively, at a rate
higher than the nominal 35 per cent (for instance, it is 42 per cent for
1994-95).
This higher rate has not hurt my grandson; since his income is below Pounds
3,445, he has been able to reclaim fully the tax paid by the trust. But the
Revenue now says it has erred in previous years by allowing the full
reclaim. It says the reclaim is limited to a tax rate of 35 per cent on the
actual income in any tax year.
Unfortunately, the Revenue is correct. Your case is a graphic illustration
of the curious results that can be thrown up by the preceding-year basis of
assessment (soon to be replaced).
The form R185 - which the trustees must provide to your grandson in respect
of actual income payments made to him - will show those payments grossed up
at a tax rate of 35 per cent. The fact that the trustees may have paid tax
more or less than 35 per cent of the gross income of the year (because the
assessment is based on the income received in a different year) is
irrelevant for this purpose.
The situation is no different if it is an individual who is getting gross
interest income at a time of falling rates. The net interest received will
be reduced by the fact that the tax liability for a particular year will
exceed the individual's marginal rate for that year as a result of the
preceding-year basis of assessment.
In such cases, taxpayers often take the opportunity to close accounts and
re-open them with other deposit-takers to ensure that the opening and
closing rules of assessment apply, thus ensuring assessment on a
present-year basis. (Reply by Andrew White).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-61</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-FAAACADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941231
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Is my AVC still secure?
 -Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Two years ago, I arranged to make additional voluntary contributions (AVCs)
to my employer's pension scheme. Since then, my company has been acquired by
another group and I am concerned regarding two matters:
1. The security of my AVC. Are AVCs less secure from possible raiding than
FSAVCs?
2. Future changes in employment (the owner has been reducing staff
recently). Are AVCs less portable than FSAVCs?
There is no reason why an AVC scheme should be any less secure than an
FSAVC. Neither scheme would be portable in the true sense of the word,
although you would have a greater degree of control, particularly on
investment questions, with the FSAVC. (Reply by Andrew White of Gordon
Leighton &amp; Co.).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
