<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Weekend Money: Lloyd serves a profits ace - The week ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THURSDAY: David Lloyd Leisure, the tennis and health club company, is
expected to report pre-tax profits for the year to end-September of Pounds
7.5m, ahead by more than 30 per cent. A total dividend of 3.6p is forecast,
compared with a notional 3.25p previously.
Although only one new club was opened during the year - in Glasgow - the
group has benefited from growing membership and the good weather last
summer. Glasgow, which was opened in October 1993, has also made a good
initial contribution.
The group acquired two clubs in Hampshire last July and expects that centres
now being built in Birmingham and Bristol will open in 1995. It has a policy
of introducing two new clubs each year.
THURSDAY: Boots, which includes Britain's biggest chain of chemists among
its retailing interests, is expected to become the first of the large
retailers to reveal how it has performed during the all-important Christmas
trading period.
After a late surge, analysts are looking for a total sales increase in the
chemist shops of at least 5 per cent in the second half so far.
Full-year group profit forecasts are about Pounds 520m-Pounds 540m, but
could change depending on when the group completes the sale of its
pharmaceuticals division to Germany's BASF.
THURSDAY: Reg Vardy, the multi-franchise motor retail group, is expected to
announce interim pre-tax profits of between Pounds 4.6m and Pounds 5m. The
substantial increase on last year's Pounds 3.51m is helped by acquisitions
but also proves the value of the company's specialist retailing strategy.
The interim dividend is forecast to rise from 1.4p to about 1.5p.
FRIDAY: Bid speculation surrounding Scantronic Holdings is likely to
re-surface when the debt-burdened security components manufacturer and
distributor announces widely-expected losses.
Following a profits warning, the company is expected to confirm hefty
re-organisation and debt servicing costs led to pre-tax losses of Pounds
2.4m in the six months to September 30, against profits of Pounds 1.4m last
time.
