<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Markets): Five resolutions for the new year -
In the Pink / John Train has some tips on the art of successful investing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN TRAIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
John Train is chairman of Montrose Advisers, investment counsel in New York.
His latest book, The Craft of Investing, has just been published by
HarperCollins.
There are no sure ways to make money on the stock market - but here are some
suggestions.
1. Watch the company, not the stock.
A stock does not flutter hither and thither like a butterfly. When a company
is prospering its profits rise, its dividends rise with them and,
infallibly, its stock will rise to follow. The question is not if, only
when, which is unimportant.
Most investors follow the prices of their stocks anxiously in the financial
pages instead of poring over each company's reports to see if its profit
margins and return on capital are staying healthy, whether it has
interesting new products coming down the pipeline, and if it is re-investing
cash flow for growth.
Some inane people hang on to a stock that fell after they bought it. Their
aim is to wait until it regains the purchase price - and then sell it. You
often hear someone say: 'I'm waiting to sell until I can get it even.'
Unfortunately, the stock does not know what you paid for it and might not
recover at all. Or, when it does, it could be a better buy - because of
re-invested earnings - than it was originally.
Women seem fond of this manoeuvre. I suspect they think of a disappointing
stock as an unfaithful lover. After disappearing for a while, it dares to
stick up its head again. 'Take that, you cur]' cries the lady, swatting it
with her handbag, so to speak.
Obviously, the limit of irrationality is to sell your stock in a good
company just because it has gone down. 2. Take the long view.
Surtout pas de zele is an excellent rule. The big money in a portfolio is
usually made by a few companies that go up and up, year after year, until
they have made their owners rich. There are exceptions but, basically,
that's how it is done.
They have to be long-term growth companies, of course, or else there is no
reason for them to go up. An easy definition of a growth company is that its
business is good enough so that it can re-invest its cash flow for an
internal rate of return of 15 or 20 per cent. That is such an attractive
proposition that its owners will not want it to pay out high dividends.
Now, there are many ways to get shaken out of a good position: the stock
seems over-priced; your broker calls with a hot tip; or you got discouraged
by dull price action. The essential fallacy, though, is to have a trading
mentality at all. Don't] You can do splendidly through inactivity within a
consistent growth philosophy.
'Market timing' rarely works. You will, probably, be out of stocks at a
major bottom when, amid universal gloom, the tremendous snap-back comes. The
Dow doubled in six weeks in the summer of 1932 as banks crumbled and brokers
falling from high windows darkened the sun.
3 Do not fret about economics.
Investors who are not informed fully on the companies in which they own
stock usually dwell instead on economics and Great Questions such as: 'Who
will win the next election?' or 'Which way will interest rates go?'
Alas, almost all Great Questions fall into one of two categories. First,
many are unknowable. Second, those that are knowable are probably factored
into the market price already.
In the course of writing books on outstanding investors, I discovered that
they rarely talk among themselves about economics or Great Questions but,
instead, almost always about specific companies. I asked Peter Lynch, the
prodigiously successful manager of the Magellan fund, how much time he spent
on economics. 'A little less than 15 minutes a year,' he answered.
Some categories of investment professional, such as Swiss bankers, are
expected to know about many stocks in each of a number of different markets.
That is an excessively difficult assignment, so they prefer to turn the
conversation to politico-economic trends in those countries. It is a way of
satisfying a client, but seldom leads to superior performance.
4. Leave currencies alone.
My clients often ask me: 'Should we buy Chilean stocks on the chance of a
revaluation in the peso?' or 'Is the yen overpriced?' Here are two thoughts.
First, for a good company, a devaluation is essentially a unilateral wage
reduction - which cannot be all bad.
How does Glen McGargle Whiskies Ltd cope with a weak pound? It maintains its
dollar price but fails to raise wages correspondingly. So, its margins and
profitability improve. The stock price should rise to offset the weaker
currency.
How about just holding cash or equivalents in the currency you think will
rise? Investors often forget that the interest rates paid on bank deposits
or short-term bonds already reflect the market's judgment of the outlook.
Suppose I think that the new Brazilian real will gain against the Argentine
peso. Fine - but the interest rate on peso bonds should be correspondingly
higher than on the real.
Over the years, I have known very few currency services offered by banks,
brokers or funds, and available to retail investors, that actually made
money over long periods.
5. Remember that investment opportunity is the difference between the
reality and the perception.
If the prevailing view of a company or a situation generally corresponds to
the truth of the matter, then there is no investment opportunity. Yet, most
people forget that and buy popular stocks in good times, which means they
pay too much.
So, for 1995, resolve to buy only stocks that are neglected or else
misunderstood for reasons that, in turn, you understand. That way, you will
seldom over-pay. The odds will be on your side.
Good hunting]
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
