<PROFILE>_AN-FAAACACPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941231
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / The future revealed: read all about it]: Six analysts study
the prospects for international markets in 1995
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Tomorrow marks the start of a new year. What will it hold for investors  -
prosperity or another dose of financial gloom? Will 1995 be, for instance:
The year in which the dollar dies?
The year when investors begin to take Russia seriously as the cheapest of
the emerging markets?
The year of the corporate merger?
Those are just three of the predictions from our panel of forecasters: two
fund managers, two conventional strategists, one technical analyst and a
stock market historian. We asked each to guess the end-1995 level for a
number of stock market indices and several key rates.
All expect US and UK interest rates to rise over the year, but those who
expect only a minor up-tick in UK inflation also expect only a minor rise in
UK base rates. And although some are predicting further falls in gilts, no
one expects another massive setback. All are predicting a recovery in UK
equities, with the Footsie finishing anywhere between 3,200 and 3,700.
Recoveries in the Japanese stock market and emerging markets are also common
ground - although, again, views on the extent differ. The hardest market to
call has been Wall Street, perhaps because it has shown such puzzling
stamina in 1994. Their predictions are summarised on page 4.
Michael Hart, the chairman of investment management group Foreign &amp;
Colonial, is modestly optimistic about most markets. He says:
Probably the most important factor of all is what happens to the US economy.
My belief is that the high real interest rates experienced for some time
now, and the rises likely in the next month or so, will slow down the
economy by mid-year. The dollar should have a better year.
Inflation will be the key. Valuations are not too demanding if investors can
look forward to steady economic growth, low inflation, stable interest rates
and improving corporate profits.
A recession is unlikely until mid-1996 at the earliest. The stock market has
not been down in a pre-election year for 55 years.
The forecast of a 10 per cent rise for the UK market is based on the belief
that growth is likely to slow and interest rates will not be forced up to
panic levels by either internal or external forces.
The outlook for corporate profits and dividends remains good as the benefit
of higher volumes and productivity improvements come through. The market is
cheap on current estimates of 1995 and 1996 earnings, although the
Conservative party's prospects appear bleak and a Labour government probably
has not been fully discounted.
The reasons for assuming that the Japanese market will rise are:
1. The economy is steadily recovering and growth in 1995 is expected to be
ahead of that for 1994.
2. Profits are also recovering: 25 per cent increases are possible in the
manufacturing sector.
3. Inflation should remain low; thus, there should be no particular pressure
on long-term bond rates.
4. Imports are now growing strongly, which should help to stabilise the yen
and avoid trade friction with the US.
5. There are also some signs that Japanese institutions are beginning to
commit money into the market.
My forecast of a rise of more than 20 per cent for emerging markets is based
on Europe and Japan stepping up imports, and an eventual slowdown in the US.
Most of these markets are expected to perform well, but the most compelling
valuations are to be found in Latin America.
1995 will be the year when investors began to take Russia seriously as the
cheapest of the emerging markets.
David Rough, Legal &amp; General group director (investments), is the other fund
manager on our panel. He is more worried about the possibility of a hard
landing in the US than Hart, but remarkably sanguine about the medium-term
outlook for the UK. He says:
Expect a further monetary tightening around the world as governments seek to
curb any emerging signs of a pick-up in inflation.
With the UK in the vanguard of recovery, domestic interest rates have
bottomed already and begun the move upwards. But even with further interest
rate increases in prospect, the UK can continue to expect steady growth
through to the end of the century without a damaging rise in inflation.
US inflation is more of a worry, even though US interest rates started to
move upwards many months earlier than in the UK. Consequently, the
continuing risk of a hard landing in the US is significantly depressing all
world markets.
The Japanese economy is more reassuring with a pick-up in growth expected
following recent sluggishness.
Continued acceleration by the German economy could weaken the recovery of
the rest of Europe but the UK will be largely insulated from the impact of
any German rate rises because our recovery is already well-established.
The emerging economies are, therefore, the most likely to suffer from any
further rises in US interest rates or a slowdown in US growth rates. The
1994 crash in world bond markets probably went too far. Although it may be
too early yet to predict a bull market in bonds, it looks as if the worst
has been seen already. But, overall, we still prefer equities to bonds.
1995 will be remembered as the year of the corporate merger, with major
deals across many industrial and financial sectors.
Michael Hughes, head of global economics and investment strategy at BZW, is
the more optimistic of our two strategists and expects anyone with an
internationally diversified portfolio to make a modest but real capital gain
in 1995. He says:
Economies rather than markets won the competition for funds in 1994.
Liquidity was the key factor. The global recovery strengthened but sapped
the available savings, with the result that markets fell. Although this
shake-out has improved the valuations of many markets, few would appear to
offer exceptional value.
The UK is not one of them, although we feel that the equity market will
benefit from the strengthening dollar and exposure to economic recovery in
Europe. Corporate mergers and acquisitions could also propel prices. Higher
domestic UK interest rates will, however, limit the adjustment of gilt
yields despite an improving budget deficit.
Most progress during the early months may be concentrated on Japan, where
the economic recovery at least appears to be materialising as the yen falls.
But this will take time, so the expected improvement in Japanese equities
should be reasonable rather than exceptional.
The recovery in Europe seems likely to gain momentum but, in the Anglo
markets, the peak of the economic growth cycle may have been achieved by the
end of 1994. Judging the timing and degree of the economic slowdown, should,
therefore, take over as a market pre-occupation.
We do not fear huge inflationary pressures at the consumer level. We are
looking for a peak US inflation rate of 4 per cent, which would suggest that
Fed funds may need to reach 7 per cent.
For the year ahead, we would expect a global balanced fund to gain by around
12 per cent, which is modest by comparison with the exceptional period in
the late '80s but very respectable against the background of 4 per cent
inflation.
This will be remembered as the year . . . when the Franc fort policy tying
the French franc with the DM is deemed no longer to be feasible nor
desirable.
Nicholas Knight, deputy managing director of Nomura Research, was
outstandingly bullish a year ago. Now, he is outstandingly cautious. He
says:
Stop-go-stop is likely to be the UK government's tactics for 1995 through
1997. This prognosis is not good for financial markets. Tight fiscal policy
and higher base rates in 1995 will kill growth faster than currently
expected, and cause downward revisions to corporate earnings estimates.
Gilts will take no comfort; fear of a big pre-election bribe, therefore,
could force gilt yields higher even if inflation remains low in the short
term.
In these circumstances, the equity market looks vulnerable, especially in
the first half. If 1995 is indeed a 'slowdown' year in a cyclical context,
valuations are still dangerously high. With UK institutions more interested
in gilts, retail investors more interested in cash and overseas investors
returning home, buy-backs and bids will be insufficient to drive the market
dramatically higher. Indeed, it could go lower, perhaps, if international
influences are as negative as we think. Higher short rates in the US,
therefore, may spark a consolidation phase for the US equity market as money
flees to the safety of cash deposits. Such has been the flood of American
money overseas in recent times that all equity markets, not just the Dow,
will feel the draught.
1995 will be remembered as the year when cyclical optimism about budget
deficits gave way to secular pessimism.
Robin Griffiths, technical analyst at research house James Capel, who warns
that he only makes year-end forecasts for fun, expects world markets to
touch bottom late in February, roughly a year after they peaked. He says:
The trend for the current year has been negative for bonds and equities all
around the world, and this will continue into the new year. Our models
indicate a low in late February to early March. We could see the FT-SE 100
at 2,680 by then. The US Dow might get to 3,200. But unless a depression
starts - there is a risk, but we bet against it - the rest of the year
should see earnings recover and stocks rise. If that is accompanied with
inflation, then equities rise a lot.
This year's down-trends will continue to late February 1995. Then, we get a
positive reversal. By then, the US Fed will have raised rates enough to have
cooled the economy without killing it and the growth in earnings will then
be able to drive equities ahead. Later, the dollar will end its rally and
become weak.
The dollar has actually been in a down-trend for 25 years but has still been
thought of as the main reserve currency. During this year, it will be
downgraded and no longer used as the dominant unit of account. The yen will
dominate the Pacific region and the D-mark or Ecu will dominate Europe.
This is the year in which the dollar will die.
David Schwartz, a stockmarket historian, is a one-man band - unlike the rest
of our panel. He says:
The critical issue that will drive stock market prices up is the next US
presidential election, due in 1996. The year preceding an election has been
a constant winner for UK shareholders since 1951. The average pre-election
year profit was over 20 per cent.
Because the stock market anticipates the real economy, it is good to own
shares in the preceding calendar year. Since 25 per cent of all FT-SE 100
company profits emanate from the US, UK investors benefit from this US
domestic issue.
1995 will be remembered as the year the UK stock market scaled a 'wall of
worry'.
</TEXT>
