<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 94 / Bosnian Serbs 'to sign truce'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Serb leaders last night said they would sign a four-month ceasefire
agreement today while the Moslem-led Bosnian government called in a senior
UN official for last-minute negotiations. Mr Radovan Karadzic, Bosnian Serb
leader, and General Ratko Mladic, Serb military commander, at noon today
will sign the cessation of hostilities, on one side, and General Sir Michael
Rose, Commander of UN forces in Bosnia, on the other. However, in an ominous
note for the ceasefire, about 30 shells yesterday hit the Bihac town centre,
a UN 'safe area', slightly wounding a UN peacekeeper.
After talks in Sarajevo, Gen Rose said: 'The ball is in their court, not in
ours any more,' in regard to the Bosnian government, which urged him to put
more muscle into the ceasefire agreement. Fearing the truce will freeze Serb
military gains, the government is seeking the withdrawal of Serb forces
round the northwestern enclave of Bihac and the demilitarisation of
Sarajevo. Mr Yasushi Akashi, top UN envoy in former Yugoslavia, will travel
to Sarajevo in an effort to persuade the Bosnian government to endorse the
truce, which was due to come into force tomorrow.
It is calling for the opening roads to the city - a more ambitious proposal
than the deal negotiated earlier this month by Mr Jimmy Carter, the former
US president. Sarajevo yesterday ended its 1,000th day under siege. Bosnian
Serb leaders, who control 70 per cent of the war-torn country, are unlikely
to lift their siege of the city, half of which Serbs lay claim to.
</TEXT>
