<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / Markets Report: Political worries push peseta to record low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Concern that political troubles could prompt the fall of the government
yesterday drove the Spanish peseta to a record low, writes Philip Gawith.
Spanish markets have been rocked recently by allegations of government
involvement in undercover operations against Eta, the Basque separatist
group. After touching a low of Pta 85.28 against the D-Mark, the peseta
closed in London at Pta 85.15 , from Pta 84.62.
The Italian lira was also a victim of political worries, and general D-Mark
strength. It breached the crucial level of L1,050 against the D-Mark, to
touch L1.050.10, from L1,045.
In Mexico, by contrast, markets rallied, with interest rates falling and the
peso recovering sharply. In New York the new peso rose 10 centavos to close
at 4.875 compared with 4.975 on Wednesday.
The Canadian dollar continued to weaken, despite reported central bank
intervention, finishing at CDollars 1.407 from CDollars 1.403.
The US dollar recovered from its sharp fall on Wednesday afternoon in New
York, where it touched lows around DM1.54 and Y98.6, to close at DM1.5507
and Y99.68.
Traders stressed again that liquidity was very poor, and this was
accentuating price movements.
Mr Felipe Gonzalez, Spain's prime minister, sought to calm markets by saying
he would not call an early general election. Arguably, this achieved the
reverse effect. Mr Malcolm Barr, international economist at Chemical Bank in
London, commented: 'This only added to the markets' nervousness because it
was seen as a sign of the depths of the crisis. There is a feeling this
could be a bit like the Berlusconi investigations which don't end until the
roots are traced right to the top.'
'The suspicion has been created that Mr Gonzalez and members of his
government knew what was going on, and that Gonzalez could be forced to
resign if any evidence came to light,' said Mr Barr. He said Spanish
economic fundamentals were also not that good, 'and this sort of development
forces the market to reappraise what is going on.'
Mr David Williams, European economist at Merrill Lynch, commented: 'The
basic problem for the peseta moving forward is that Spain's extremely high
propensity to import, coupled with a gradual loss of cost competitiveness,
points to a trend deterioration in the current account.'
The Bank of Spain has said it will defend the value of the peseta, and
economists believe that if it weakens to around Pta 86/86.5, the bank will
be forced to raise interest rates.
The catalyst for the peso's appreciation was news that that the US is
working with Mexico on a credit facility to stop the currency's recent fall.
A US Treasury official said also that Mexico had not drawn on the Dollars
7bn currency support line provided to it by the US and Canada to support the
peso.
The official comment followed market rumours which saw the dollar plummet by
around three pfennigs and two yen during afternoon New York trade on
Wednesday.
In France leading commercial banks raised their base rate to 8.25 per cent
from 7.95 per cent, but the Bank of France held its intervention rate at 5
per cent.
The intervention rate has been at 5 per cent since May 24. Analysts said the
central bank had sought to keep its intervention rate above the German repo
rate, which has been at 4.85 per cent since July.
French inflation is only 1.6 per cent, but the central bank wishes to keep
the franc stable against the D-Mark.
The franc closed unchanged at FFr3.455 against the D-Mark.
In the UK short sterling contracts fell by 10-15 basis points. They took
their lead from the collapse in gilt prices. Mr Richard Phillips, analyst at
brokers, GNI said the tone had been set by heavy selling from two US hedge
funds. 'It has been a combination of extremely thin markets and some quite
lumpy orders.'
The March contract finished at 92.52, from 92.66.
Sterling had an erratic day, finishing more than a pfennig lower against the
D-Mark, at DM2.4183, from DM2.4309. Against the dollar it was up by 1 1/2
cents, at Dollars 1.5595, from Dollars 1.5447.
The Bank of England provided UK money markets with Pounds 706m assistance,
after declaring a Pounds 800m daily shortage.
</TEXT>
