<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / Athena suppliers seeking legal advice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Creditors of Athena, the poster and card retailer forced into administrative
receivership by its parent Pentos, were yesterday seeking legal advice about
the company's action.
Mr John Allan, a director of Bod Prods, a Sheffield-based supplier of
novelty stationery, said he understood throughout he was dealing with Pentos
and that he agreed to supply Athena only after a Pounds 45m rights issue
came through for Pentos earlier this year. He said his company, which
supplied children's stationery decorated with spiders and slugs, was owed
Pounds 75,000.
Mr Allan, who received an urgent fax from Athena on December 19 for further
supplies worth Pounds 25,009, said last night he was told by receivers Grant
Thornton that he would not get any of his money. He added that in 16 years
in business he had never before had a bad debt of more than Pounds 5,000.
Mr Chris Marler of Davy Marler, also suppliers of novelty stationery who
said his company is owed Pounds 60,000, said last night he knew there was a
degree of risk but thought that Pentos plc would stand behind Athena.
Pentos, whose main company is Dillons the booksellers, said on Wednesday
that the board had decided that it should not inject further funds into
Athena's UK business because there was no prospect of its returning to
profit in the foreseeable future.
Earlier this week, Pentos had changed the name of the Athena subsidiary from
Pentos Retailing Group to Athena Holdings. The directors of the latter then
called in the receivers.
Mr Bill McGrath, Pentos chief executive, said in an interview on Wednesday
'We couldn't give it (Athena) away.'
Mr Marler said yesterday: 'To ring fence a bit of the business like this is
morally reprehensible'. Both he and Mr Allan asked whether Athena should
have been trading if the company was in such poor shape that it could not be
'given away'.
Both suppliers made clear that their potential losses would not threaten the
viability of their own businesses. Pentos declined to comment yesterday.
Camden Graphics, the greeting card publisher, is believed to be owed Pounds
200,000 by Athena.
The biggest creditors are the landlords of the Athena shops who are owed
Pounds 3.5m and, at least on paper, Cartel, the management buy-in which took
over the publishing, manufacturing and wholesaling businesses of Athena
International in June for a maximum of Pounds 1.9m.
Mr David Clipsham, who has in the past worked for both the Athena retail and
publishing businesses and for WH Smith, said yesterday that Cartel was
protected. The company had a five-year supply agreement with Pentos with a
minimum supply guarantee based on previous performance for three years.
Mr Clipsham declined to give a value for the agreement. Athena's turnover
was Pounds 12m at the time of the management buy-in and the company accounts
for about one third of Cartel's business.
The original legal agreement with Pentos, Mr Clipsham added, also protected
the company against any loss over goods supplied.
</TEXT>
