<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / First Choice makes a 'new start' in links with WestLB
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
First Choice Holidays yesterday abandoned two of the three legs of its
strategic alliance with Germany's Westdeutsche Landesbank, which controls a
21 per cent stake in it.
The group also announced that Mr Wolfgang Trube, chief executive of a WestLB
subsidiary, would be joining the board as a non-executive director. He will
replace Mr Christopher Rodrigues, chief executive of Thomas Cook, which is
90 per cent owned by WestLB.
Thomas Cook bought the 21 per cent stake in First Choice, formerly known as
Owners Abroad, last year, helping it to defeat a hostile takeover bid from
Airtours, a rival tour operator. The Owners Abroad management at the time
expected substantial savings to follow through co-operation with LTU, the
German travel company 34 per cent owned by WestLB.
First Choice will retain its retail agreement with Thomas Cook, but will end
attempts to realise economies through links with LTU. Mr Trube's task will
be to monitor WestLB's investment and to provide an informal channel for
links with LTU.
'I think it's a new start,' said Mr Francis Baron, First Choice chief
executive yesterday. 'It's a new start on a very pragmatic, business
orientated basis, aiming to secure benefits for all our shareholders.'
Dr Johannes Ringel, chairman of Thomas Cook and a member of the WestLB
board, said that WestLB remained 'committed and supportive shareholders and
believed that the company has a bright future ahead'.
The alliance always promised far more than it ever delivered. At the same
time the management structure of First Choice changed out of all
recognition.
Shortly after defeating the Airtours bid, the chairman and managing director
of Owners Abroad resigned after disclosing that full-year profits would be
only half market expectations.
New management found that the strategic alliance was failing to win cost
savings on the airline side through shared aircraft maintenance, fuel buying
and spares purchasing, and on the tour operating side through greater buying
power in booking holiday accommodation. The commercial agreement covering
these two issues was terminated yesterday. Instead, a more informal
arrangement is expected through Mr Trube's involvement.
First Choice thanked Mr Rodrigues, who has a marketing background, for his
contribution to rebuilding the company. But it is understood that his
presence on the board was creating problems in the market place for
holidays, with other multiple retailers suspicious of the Thomas Cook link.
Mr Trube, 52, is now chief executive of Westdeutsche Spielbanken, which runs
several casinos in Germany. He has been with WestLB since 1970, and was
involved in the bank's acquisition of Thomas Cook.
</TEXT>
