<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / The Lex Column: Derivatives accounting
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Derivatives pose a challenge to those who devise accounting standards, not
least because part of the raison d'etre of complex financial instruments is
to circumvent existing disclosure rules. But derivatives have the power to
transform a company's risks - for little cash outlay  - in a way which is
not reflected in conventional historical cost accounting.
The UK's Accounting Standards Board, currently examining ways of improving
financial reporting in this area, is thus right to tackle the issue. The ASB
is likely next year to recommend increased disclosure so that users of
accounts get more information about the risks taken on by the company. Thus,
companies may be required to disclose the impact of fluctuations in exchange
or interest rates on balance sheet ratios. Some groups release this
information voluntarily now, as part of a review of treasury policy in the
operating and financial review which forms part of a set of accounts. The
ASB should go further, for example requiring companies to recognise
unrealised gains and losses incurred on derivatives.
Given derivatives' inherent complexity, though, there is a danger that
greater disclosure will sow confusion rather than understanding among users
of accounts. But if the process of complying with such rules helps companies
better to identify the risks they are letting themselves in for, neither
management nor investors should complain.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6221 Commodity Contracts Brokers, Dealers.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
