<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / The Lex Column: Australia
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Is Australia about to embark on another vicious boom bust cycle? With bond
yields in excess of 10 per cent, investors appear to have reached their
conclusions already. The chief worry is inflation, even though it is running
below 3 per cent. Interest rates have been raised by 2.75 percentage points
since mid-August and tax increases are in the pipeline, but this may not be
enough to curb overheating. The drought has not prevented the economy
growing at 5 per cent. The reliance on commodities, which account for more
than 60 per cent of exports, limits the effectiveness of monetary or fiscal
policy as a way of controlling economic growth.
Memories of the last recession may have contributed to an over-reaction. The
current account deficit is a concern, but the drought has restrained
exports, while import growth has been partially stimulated by capital
equipment expenditure. This provides further evidence that industry has
learnt from previous cycles, and is increasing investment to retain
competitiveness. Inflation should peak at 5.5 per cent in late 1996, not
enough to justify current bond yields. Industrial stocks already look
undervalued on earnings estimates for the next two years. The Australian
dollar is tied to commodity prices, and is likely to strengthen steadily. An
excessive appreciation would, of course, erode industrial competitiveness in
the longer term, but a strengthening dollar should attract overseas cash,
providing further support for the markets. Shares, down 17 per cent since
February, look over sold.
</TEXT>
