<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / The Lex Column: Deutsche Bank
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
If ITT's sale of its financial services arm is in shareholders' interests,
the reverse may be the case for Deutsche Bank, which is paying a net Dollars
900m for ITT Commercial Finance. True, Deutsche will be able to reap
benefits from putting together its existing north American asset-based
lending activities with those of the ITT subsidiary, and will gain access to
thousands of new customers in north America and elsewhere in the world.
But the bank will also have to write off substantial goodwill following the
acquisition. No figure for this has been disclosed, but analysts put it at
Dollars 700m. The acquisition adds Dollars 3.75bn of receivables to
Deutsche's balance sheet, but the net effect of the deal will be an
appreciable deterioration in the bank's core, tier one capital ratio. Other
recent acquisitions, both in Germany and abroad, have also involved a large
goodwill element. Given the bank's reluctance to sell the bulk of its
industrial holdings, the danger is that Deutsche will be obliged to turn to
shareholders to restore its capital base.
Investors may be reluctant to contemplate this, as the strategy behind the
acquisitions makes questionable sense. Recent purchases in Spain, Italy and
now the US enhance the bank's position in these countries, but do not
transform the bank's global competitiveness or its earnings power. The bank
should consider pulling out of peripheral markets - especially in Spain and
Italy - and concentrating its resources on developing a world-class
investment banking operation.
</TEXT>
