<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the words of S. Sondheim, comedy tonight. On BBC1 Dawn French and
Jennifer Saunders resume the partnership they interrupted for solo careers.
Saunders has emerged as the more talented of the two, or perhaps the
shrewder judge of her own talents: Absolutely Fabulous has been
epoch-making, while French's forays into comedy and drama have shown her to
be less versatile and a less good judge of scripts. Never mind; they are
together again at 9.30, and the BBC's recent return to Dickensian costume
does not go unnoticed.
For some time Rory Bremner has been providing genuine satire, abetted by the
intelligent and incisive double act of Johns Fortune and Bird in the
isolated fastness of Channel 4. There is usually more pointed comment in
five minutes of his shows than the flailing spite of Spitting Image and
complacent juvenilia of Have I Got News for You put together. A BAFTA award
this year was well deserved. Rory Bremner's Christmas Turkey at 10pm should
provide plenty of stuffing and lots of sauce.
</TEXT>
